                               Call for Papers=20
 =20
                         Speech Communication Journal=20
                               Special Issue on=20
                  "Evaluating new methods and models for=20
                 advanced speech-based interactive systems"=20
 =20
  In recent years there has been a growth of research focusing on=20
  communication models for speech-based interactive systems that go=20
  beyond those currently used in commercial spoken dialogue systems.=20
  One aim of this research is to increase the system's communicative=20
  competence by incorporating more advanced characteristics of spoken=20
  interaction including speech segmentation, disfluencies, turn-taking,=20
  emotions, and adaptation. Another research direction involves dialogue =

  strategies: the development of more advanced models of dialogue that=20
  enable more natural, more robust, and more efficient communication. To =

  support these additional functionalities various advanced =
architectures=20
  have been developed that incorporate sophisticated components and=20
  techniques not present in current commercial systems. At the same =
time,=20
  researchers have been applying new methods for the automatic design =
and=20
  optimization of spoken dialogue systems, such as example-based =
learning=20
  and reinforcement learning,=20
 =20
  The aim of this special issue is to explore new evaluation techniques=20
  and strategies as applied to advanced dialogue systems, including new=20
  models and methods. Papers should discuss under what circumstances=20
  each evaluation technique should be used, along with their strengths=20
  and weaknesses. Papers should illustrate how the technique and =
strategy=20
  was used to discover problems with the interactive dialogue system, =
and=20
  the degree to which the system was improved using new models and =
design=20
  methods.=20
 =20
  Original, previously unpublished submissions addressing some (or all)=20
  of the following questions are encouraged:=20
 =20
  1. What characteristics of spoken language interaction can=20
  and should be incorporated into advanced spoken dialogue systems?=20
 =20
  2. What are the best methods for designing such systems? To=20
  what extent are automatic design methods appropriate or possible?
 =20
  3. What criteria can be defined for the evaluation of the=20
  performance of advanced spoken dialogue systems?
 =20
  4. Under what circumstances should these criteria be used?=20
 =20
  5. How effective are these criteria in isolating problems=20
  with a dialogue strategy and in measuring how correction of the=20
  problems improves the dialogue?=20
 =20
  6. How can these criteria be used to compare and evaluate=20
  alternative dialogue strategies and methods for the design and=20
  implementation of dialogue systems?=20
 =20
  7. How can these criteria be used to compare the pre-
  modification version and the post-modification version of a dialogue=20
  strategy as developers attempt to improve the dialogue strategy?=20
 =20
  8. How can the evaluation process be streamlined so that=20
  it can be frequently and effectively applied to the improvement and=20
  comparison of dialogue strategies?=20
 =20
  =20
  Guest Editors=20
 =20
  Michael McTear, University of Ulster, UK mf.mctear@ulster.ac.uk=20
  Kristiina Jokinen, University of Helsinki, Finland=20
  kristiina.jokinen@helsinki.fi=20
  James Larson, Oregon Graduate Institute, Oregon, USA =
jim@larson-tech.com
 =20
 =20
  Important Dates=20
 =20
  Submission Deadline: 30th June 2007=20
  Notification of Acceptance: 30th November 2007=20
  Final manuscript due: 31 January 2008=20
  Tentative Publication Date: June 2008=20
 =20
  Submission Procedure=20
 =20
  Prospective authors should follow the regular guidelines of the Speech =

  Communication journal for electronic submission=20
  (http://ees.elsevier.com/specom). During submission authors must =
select=20
  the Article Type: "Special Issue: Spoken Dialogue Technology, not
  "Regular=20
  Paper", and also select Professor Marc Swerts as the handling =
Editor-in-
  Chief.=20
 =20
  Text of Call for Papers
 =20

http://www.elsevier.com/authored_subject_sections/P05/CFP/cfp_spokendialo=
gu
 e.pdf

